22–1356":"1322–1356","1323–1369":"1323–1369","1363":"1363","1361":"1361","1382":"1382","1390":"1390","1415":"1415","1369":"1369","1368":"1368","1345":"1345","1323":"1323","1356":"1356","1322":"1322","1441":"1441","1342":"1342","about 1356":"about 1356","1407":"1407","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Raby, Cheshire, England":"Raby, Cheshire, England","Stapleford, Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Bruen","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Dermot, Finbarr.","Irish: variant of   Breen  .","North German (<b>Brün</b>): from Middle Low German <i>brūn</i> ‘brown’, hence probably a nickname for someone with brown hair or a dark complexion or for someone who habitually wore brown clothes. Compare   Braun   and   Brun  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Breen","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Brennan, Conan, John Patrick, Kiera, Niall.","Irish: either a shortened form of   McBreen   or an Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Braoin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Braon</i>’, a byname meaning ‘moisture, drop’.","Norwegian: habitational name from the farm name Bre(d)en, from Old Norse <i>breithr</i> ‘wide’ + <i>-en</i> from <i>vin</i> ‘meadow’."]}]},{"name":"Ellen","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Helen  , although now no longer associated with that name. Initial <i>H-</i> tended to be added and dropped rather capriciously, leading to many doublets (  compare for example  Esther   and   Hester  ). It is also sometimes used as a short form of   Eleanor  , to which, however, it is unrelated."],"variants":[{"name":"Eleanor","meanings":["From an Old French respelling of the Old Provençal name <i>Alienor</i>. This has sometimes been taken as a derivative of   Helen  , but it is more probably of Germanic derivation (the first element being <i>ali</i> ‘other, foreign’ the second is obscure). The name was introduced to England by  Eleanor of Aquitaine  (  1122–1204 ), who came from Aquitaine in south-west France to be the wife of  King Henry II . It was also borne by Eleanor of Provence, the wife of  Henry III , and Eleanor of Castile, wife of  Edward I ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":37,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Ellen Bruen was born in 1345, in Cheshire, England, her father, Hugh FitzRoger, was 24 and her mother, Margery Picmere, was 22. She married Hugh Hulse in 1363. They were the parents of at least 3 sons. She died in 1390, in Cheshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 45."},"et":{"1345–1390":"1345–1390","1342–1407":"1342–1407","1361–1415":"1361–1415","1368–1441":"1368–1441","1369–1441":"1369–1441","1322–1356":"1322–1356","1323–1369":"1323–1369","1363":"1363","1361":"1361","1382":"1382","1390":"1390","1415":"1415","1369":"1369","1368":"1368","1345":"1345","1323":"1323","1356":"1356","1322":"1322","1441":"1441","1342":"1342","about 1356":"umbes 1356","1407":"1407","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Raby, Cheshire, England":"Raby, Cheshire, England","Stapleford, Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England"},"fi":{"1345–1390":"1345–1390","1342–1407":"1342–1407","1361–1415":"1361–1415","1368–1441":"1368–1441","1369–1441":"1369–1441","1322–1356":"1322–1356","1323–1369":"1323–1369","1363":"1363","1361":"1361","1382":"1382","1390":"1390","1415":"1415","1369":"1369","1368":"1368","1345":"1345","1323":"1323","1356":"135